{"key":"post-9588566","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>9588566</id>\n<content>If you have less than about 35% humidity in your house during the winter, your heating bills will nearly double due to the fact that dry air can't hold heat.&amp;nbsp; Moist air holds heat due to the thermal mass of the moisture.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;If you get condensation on the walls, it's not because of too much humidity, it means you don't have good insulation.&amp;nbsp; If necessary, get some 1/4&quot; styrofoam from the hardware store and staple it to your walls.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Everyone should run a humidifier indoors in the winter.&amp;nbsp; It's not just for your mushroom projects or heating bills, it's for your own respiratory health.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>9588577</next>\n<prev>9588515</prev>\n<first>9588446</first>\n<last>9588640</last>\n<when>1231694278</when>\n<utime>01/11/09 07:17 PM</utime>\n</post>"}